00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:51.360
then those two things will annihilate, and&nbsp;
so they are able to be presented this way.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:52.800 --> 00:19:00.720
So the kind of shimmering reality that the quantum&nbsp;
physicists like to talk about, where we have these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:06.600
fields, and these fields have all these emergent&nbsp;
pairs of little particles, you know, that are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:11.700
being quickly created and then annihilated and&nbsp;
they appear and then they disappear, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:16.140
just for a split second, you know, and so&nbsp;
this is some kind of really strange thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:21.300
that that's how they think. What we're seeing is&nbsp;
something parallel to that here in this world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.020 --> 00:19:31.500
that we're able to create these box anti-box&nbsp;
pairs and then they're annihilated a second later.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:37.740
So if this is really strange, think about it&nbsp;
the following way, which which makes it maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:44.940
more familiar. So when you're doing ordinary&nbsp;
arithmetic with fractions, say three over five,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:52.740
okay, you all know that you can replace that by&nbsp;
multiplying top and bottom by whatever we want,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.740 --> 00:19:59.400
say like by two. So three over five is the same&nbsp;
as six over ten. So what have we done there? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:05.640
we've introduced a new factor on the top and the&nbsp;
bottom. The two factors happen to be the same,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:11.820
but they're in different places, so they're&nbsp;
playing different roles, sort of like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:17.160
red dot and this black dot. They're sort of the&nbsp;
same except that they're different because one's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:21.600
red and one's black. And correspondingly, you&nbsp;
know, one of the twos is in the numerator, one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:26.760
of the twos is in the denominator, and so you can&nbsp;
take three fifths and if you like you can quickly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:33.780
change it to six over ten, or you can multiply it&nbsp;
by three and get 9 over 15. Right, you're doing it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:33.780 --> 00:20:40.200
something very similar. You're creating something&nbsp;
more complicated by adding some more factors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:44.580
but in these two different ways which are sort of&nbsp;
balanced, so they're sort of kind of a duality.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.420 --> 00:20:50.880
So it's actually not that&nbsp;
unfamiliar from some point of view.

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:57.660
Okay, so now I think with this sort&nbsp;
of general orientation I think we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:03.600
can now go back to the development that&nbsp;
we've already had in terms of zeros and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:08.400
natural numbers and poly numbers and multi&nbsp;
numbers and sort of redo all those things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:16.440
but just starting with the box anti-box point of&nbsp;
view. So we just carry on down, and it's I think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:22.140
an interesting exercise, and we're going to&nbsp;
have to look very carefully at that because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:22.140 --> 00:21:32.040
we've seen that these particle anti-particle&nbsp;
things have some curious, maybe even disturbing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:40.740
properties when we are doing basic arithmetic just&nbsp;
with, say, the zero box and the anti-zero box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:48.300
So it might be that when we restrict&nbsp;
ourselves to just boxed arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:55.020
that those curious aspects are hidden&nbsp;
from sight. In fact, that's sort of what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:55.020 --> 00:22:00.720
I'm thinking will happen, that those sort of&nbsp;
anomalous kind of things that we're seeing are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:08.400
are not really visible parts of the mathematical&nbsp;
or arithmetical world that we're going to create.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:12.360
We're ultimately going to be interested in&nbsp;
box arithmetic, but we want to have this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:16.740
symmetry because these guys are going&nbsp;
to be crucial ingredients in the boxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:18.540 --> 00:22:23.880
So that's a lot of fun. Maybe some of you would&nbsp;
like to, you know, try that out yourself and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:29.280
see how far you get in terms of building up&nbsp;
a consistent theory. Ultimately, we want very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:36.360
careful definitions and theorems and proofs, etc.&nbsp;
But, you know, exactly how we're going to do that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:36.360 --> 00:22:42.749
that may be still some ways away. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Walberger, thanks for listening. [Music]

